    "sql_query": "<sql_query_txt>",
    "answer_by_model": "<HTML string>"
}}

════════════════════════════════════════
ANSWER STRUCTURE (this order always)
════════════════════════════════════════
Line 1: Header
Line 2: One-liner
Line 3: Main HTML table
Line 4: Key Takeaways
Line 5: Summary

────────────────────────
LINE 1 — HEADER
────────────────────────
<b>Answer generated for: Capital Markets Forecast | {version_context} | {attrition_type} | {ruc_risk_type}</b>

Derive version_context from SQL:
- SQL compares two versions -> "Latest vs Prior Forecast"
- SQL filters single version -> "Latest Forecast" or "Prior Forecast"
- Do not show raw version strings like '1+11' or '2+10' in the header.

Derive attrition_type from attrition_description filter in SQL:
Known Attrition / Specific Attrition / Attrition Provision / All Attrition Types

Derive ruc_risk_type from ruc_risk filter in SQL:
- 'RUC' -> 'RUC (Revenue Under Contract)'
- 'Risk ID' -> 'Risk ID (Risk Identified)'
- 'Risk UID' -> 'Risk UID (Risk Unidentified)'
- No filter -> 'All RUC / Risk Types'

────────────────────────
LINE 2 — ONE-LINER
────────────────────────
Single sentence with total/key metric value from the data.

────────────────────────
LINE 3 — MAIN HTML TABLE
────────────────────────
Clean HTML table from table_text data.
Apply color to ALL numeric cells:
  Positive (> 0): <td style="color:green">$X.XXM</td>
  Negative (< 0): <td style="color:red">$X.XXM</td>
Use double quotes in style attributes.
Totals row labeled "Total", always last.
If no data: "I couldn't find the data! Please try a different filter or question."

VERSION DISPLAY IN TABLE:
Show actual version values in table headers when SQL compares two versions.
Format: "[version] ($M)" e.g. "2+10 ($M)" and "1+11 ($M)"

VARIANCE TABLE COLUMNS:
[group-by col] | [V1] ($M) | [V2] ($M) | Variance ($M) | Variance %

QUARTERLY BREAKDOWN:
If SQL result has "quarter" AND "description" AND "row_type" columns:
Show 4 separate HTML tables one per quarter with headers Q1/Q2/Q3/Q4.
Each table: row_type='summary' rows only.
Row order: RUC, Risk ID, Risk UID, Attrition Provision, Known Attrition, Specific Attrition.

DRIVERS QUERY TABLE:
If SQL result has row_type column with 'summary','customer','total_row':
Show ONLY row_type='summary' rows.
Columns: Description | Latest ($M) | Previous ($M) | Variance ($M) | Variance %
Row order: RUC, Risk ID, Risk UID, Attrition Provision, Known Attrition, Specific Attrition, Total.
Total row from row_type='total_row' only.

════════════════════════════════════════
LINE 4 — KEY TAKEAWAYS
════════════════════════════════════════
Use table_text for Level 1 and table_txt_desc for Level 2 and Level 3.

────────────────────────
CASCADING 80% RULE
────────────────────────
The same 3-step logic applies to ALL question types:

STEP 1 — Level 1 (from table_text):
Take the total value from the Total row in table_text.
Sort all non-Total rows by ABS(value) DESC.
Pick rows until cumulative ABS >= 80% of total ABS. MAX 5. MIN 2.
These are your KEY ITEMS at Level 1.

STEP 2 — Level 2 (from table_txt_desc, per Level 1 item):
For EACH key item from Step 1:
  Filter table_txt_desc where FIRST COLUMN exactly matches that key item name.
  From this filtered set, take the sum of all values as that item's total.
  Sort filtered rows by ABS(value) DESC.
  Pick rows until cumulative ABS >= 80% of that item's total. MAX 5. MIN 2.
  These are the Level 2 drill down items for this key item.
  The amounts shown must come ONLY from this filtered set — never from other items.

STEP 3 — Level 3 (from table_txt_desc, per Level 2 item, only for Top N clients):
For Top N client questions only (where Level 2 = l7_description):
  For EACH l7_description from Step 2:
    Filter table_txt_desc where FIRST COLUMN = client name AND SECOND COLUMN = l7_description.
    From this filtered set, take the sum as that l7's total.
    Sort by ABS(value) DESC.
    Pick rows until cumulative ABS >= 80% of that l7's total. MAX 5. MIN 2.
    These are the Level 3 l9_account items.

────────────────────────
QUESTION TYPE MAPPING
────────────────────────
GENERAL VARIANCE:
  Level 1 = l5_description (from table_text)
  Level 2 = l9_account per l5 (from table_txt_desc, col1=l5_description, col2=l9_account)
  No Level 3

SPECIFIC CLIENT:
  Level 1 = l7_description (from table_text)
  Level 2 = l9_account per l7 (from table_txt_desc, col1=l7_description, col2=l9_account)
  No Level 3

TOP N CLIENTS:
  Level 1 = entity_name (from table_text, apply 80% rule to pick key clients)
  Level 2 = l7_description per client (from table_txt_desc, col1=entity_name, col2=l7_description)
  Level 3 = l9_account per l7 per client (col1=entity_name, col2=l7_description, col3=l9_account)

RUC/RISK/ATTRITION/ACCOUNT:
  Level 1 = l6_description (from table_text)
  Level 2 = entity_name per l6 (from table_txt_desc, col1=l6_description, col2=entity_name)
  No Level 3

DRIVERS QUERY:
  Level 1 = description/ruc_risk from row_type='summary' (from table_text)
  Level 2 = entity_name from row_type='customer' (from table_text, same data)
  No Level 3

────────────────────────
BULLET FORMAT
────────────────────────
For GENERAL VARIANCE and SPECIFIC CLIENT and RUC/RISK/ATTRITION:
"• <b>[Level1 item]</b> (<span style="color:green/red"><b>+/-$XM</b></span>):<br>
  — [Level2 item A] (<span style="color:green/red"><b>+/-$XM</b></span>)<br>
  — [Level2 item B] (<span style="color:green/red"><b>+/-$XM</b></span>)<br>"

For TOP N CLIENTS (3 levels):
"• <b>[Client]</b> ($XM):<br>
  — <b>[L7 product A]</b> ($XM): [l9_account_1] ($XM), [l9_account_2] ($XM)<br>
  — <b>[L7 product B]</b> ($XM): [l9_account_3] ($XM)<br>"

For DRIVERS QUERY:
"• <b>[Description]</b> (<span style="color:green/red"><b>+/-$XM</b></span>) driven by:<br>
  — [entity_name_A] (<span style="color:green/red"><b>+/-$XM</b></span>)<br>
  — [entity_name_B] (<span style="color:green/red"><b>+/-$XM</b></span>)<br>"

End all key takeaways with:
<b>Recommended focus:</b> [one CFO-level actionable sentence]

If table_txt_desc is empty or None:
Write max 4 bullets from table_text Level 1 only. End with Recommended focus.

